'''Ōji-no-Kami''' (王子神) is one of the deities in Japan. It is also simply referred to as '''Ōji''', and the faith surrounding it is called '''Ōji Shinkō'''.

== Ōji Faith ==
In ancient Japan, there was a belief of enshrining divine personas that branched off as child deities of the main deity at a shrine, referred to as {{ill|Wakamiya|ja|若宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakamiya|qq=}} or {{ill|Mikogami|ja|御子神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikogami|qq=}}, often alongside maternal deities with shamanic characteristics. Over time, with the progression of {{ill|Syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism|ja|神仏習合|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=}}, the Buddhist concept of {{ill|Dōji|ja|童子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dōji|qq=}}, depicted as children attending Buddhas, merged with these young deities and came to be known as Ōji. Shrines dedicated to Ōji also adopted the name.

This syncretism was particularly prominent in the {{ill|Kumano Faith|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Faith|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|qq=}}, where by the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}, five deities of the {{ill|Kumano Gongen|ja|熊野十二所権現|lt=Kumano Twelve Deities|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Gongen|qq=}}, known as the {{ill|Kumano_Ninety-Nine_Ōji#Five_Major_Ōji_Shrines|ja|五所王子|Kumano_Ninety-Nine_Ōji#Five_Major_Ōji_Shrines=Kumano_Ninety-Nine_Ōji#Five_Major_Ōji_Shrines|lt=Five Goshō Ōji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano_Ninety-Nine_Ōji#Five_Major_Ōji_Shrines|qq=}}, gained prominence. Among these, the {{ill|Wakaōji|ja|若王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakaōji|qq=}} or {{ill|Nyakuichi Ōji|ja|若一王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nyakuichi Ōji|qq=}} deity, depicted as a boy or girl, was widely enshrined when {{ill|Kumano Gongen|ja|熊野権現|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Gongen|qq=}} was transferred elsewhere.

During the same era, eight deities in the form of Ōji, known as {{ill|Hachiōji Gongen|ja|八王子権現|1=Hachiōji Gongen|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiōji Gongen|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiōji Gongen|qq=}}, appeared as subordinate deities of the {{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Shrine|qq=}}'s {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|qq=}} and the {{ill|Sannō Gongen|ja|山王権現|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sannō Gongen|qq=}} at {{ill|Hiyoshi Taisha|ja|日吉大社|1=Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiyoshi Taisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiyoshi Taisha|qq=}}. These deities were revered for their miraculous powers to ward off illnesses.

== Ōji in Place Names ==
With the rise of Ōji faith, locations housing shrines dedicated to Ōji came to bear the name, spreading such toponyms across Japan.

One example is {{ill|Ōji, Kita-ku, Tokyo|ja|王子 (東京都北区)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōji, Kita-ku, Tokyo|qq=}} in {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo|qq=}}, named after the {{ill|Wakaōji Gongen Shrine|ja|若王子権現|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakaōji Gongen Shrine|qq=}}, now {{ill|Ōji Shrine|ja|王子神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōji Shrine|qq=}}. Similarly, the name of {{ill|Hachiōji, Tokyo|ja|八王子市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiōji, Tokyo|qq=}} originates from {{ill|Hachiōji Castle|ja|八王子城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiōji Castle|qq=}}, built on a mountain enshrining the {{ill|Hachioji Shrine|ja|八王子神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachioji Shrine|qq=}}.

Alternatively, some scholars suggest that "Ōji" derives from words indicating "depression" in the terrain, such as "Ōchi" (窪地) or "Ōuchi" (凹地), which describe low-lying or steeply descending areas. For instance, the area of Ōji overlooks the {{ill|Shakujii River|ja|石神井川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shakujii River|qq=}} on a hill, descending steeply towards the {{ill|Takinogawa area|ja|滝野川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takinogawa area|qq=}}.
